<sn><md>#### Divergent Boundary{.text-center}

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
* **Definition:** A boundary where two plates move **away from each other**.
* **Features/Effects:** Formation of new crust, mid-ocean ridges, rift valleys, volcanic activity.
* **Example:** Mid-Atlantic Ridge.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
![diagram](https://science8sc.weebly.com/uploads/1/3/2/7/132773018/mid-ocean-ridge-gif_orig.gif)
:::
:::
</md></sn><sn><md>#### Convergent Boundary{.text-center}

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
* **Definition:** A boundary where two plates move **towards each other**.
* **Features/Effects:** Mountain formation, deep ocean trenches, volcanic eruptions, earthquakes.
* **Types:**

   * **Continental-Continental Collision:** Forms mountains (e.g., Himalayas)
   * **Oceanic-Continental Subduction:** Oceanic plate sinks beneath continental plate (e.g., Andes Mountains)
   * **Oceanic-Oceanic Subduction:** One oceanic plate sinks under another, forming island arcs (e.g., Japan)
:::

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
![diagram](https://i.makeagif.com/media/9-27-2021/BMwMaB.gif)
:::
:::
</md></sn><sn><md>#### Transform Boundary{.text-center}
:::.row

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
* **Definition:** A boundary where two plates **slide past each other horizontally**.
* **Features/Effects:** Frequent earthquakes, little or no volcanic activity.
* **Example:** San Andreas Fault, California.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
![diagram](https://i.makeagif.com/media/9-27-2021/YQ39TW.gif)
